  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Show, don\u0026rsquo;t tell is the principle that fiction is more effective when the writer dramatizes — presents action, dialogue, and sensory detail — rather than stating conclusions directly. Instead of \u0026ldquo;She was angry,\u0026rdquo; the writer shows: \u0026ldquo;She set the glass down hard enough to crack the stem.\u0026rdquo;\nThe principle originates with Anton Chekhov\u0026rsquo;s advice: \u0026ldquo;Don\u0026rsquo;t tell me the moon is shining; show me the glint of light on broken glass.\u0026rdquo; It was formalized in craft pedagogy throughout the twentieth century and remains the most commonly taught fiction principle — and the most commonly misapplied.\n",
  "name": "Show, Don't Tell",
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "emsenn",
